Ford GoBike Data Investigation & Visualization¶

by ADELEKE ADEKOLA EMMANUEL¶

Introduction¶

The dataset, 201902-fordgobike-tripdata.csv, is downloaded from Udacity classroom and licensed by Ford GoBike. This dataset includes 183,411 trips with 16 features such as locations, time, and user attributes. There are start and end stations. I noticed that most trips happen on the same stations, so I subset the dataset by choosing top 5 trips start stations with the most trips.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Data Assesment Outcome¶

Quality Issues

  1. Missing values for; start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name

  2. Incorrect DataType for; start_time and end_time columns in object dtype, start_station_id and end_station_id columns in int64 dtype, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, and end_station_longitude columns in float64 dtype, bike_id column in int64 dtype, user_type in object dtype

  3. Some columns are not needed; start_station_id, end_station_id, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford gobike dataset consists of 183411 rows 16 columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in this dataset is duration, member_gender, and user_type column, and I'm most interested in figuring out how trip duration is dependent on other specifications from the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The feature that will help our investigation are station name / location, and user type. Also, we can extract month, day, and hour feature from start_time for further analysis. I also expect that trip duration is highly dependent on the start stations and end stations, more crowded places should receive more rides so some stations should be logging more duration sec. I also think user_type, birthyear and gender should also effect trip duration.

Univariate Data Exploration Questions¶

1: Which user type has the highest number? 2: What gender has the highest riders? 3: What is the average trip durations? 4: What is the Bike Distribution? 5: How does the Datetime affect the ride? 6: How does the Stations Analysis determine ride?

Bivariate Data Exploration Questions¶

1: What is the correlation between trip duration and age? 2: What is the dependency of trip durations on gender and on member type? 3: What is the comparison between the user types, customer and subscriber? 4: What is the correlation between Datetime and user type?

Multivariate Data Exploration Question¶

1: How is the two categorical measures gender and user type play into the relationship between trip duration and age?
